France Nantes church fire: parish volunteer admits to arson, usually kind and reticent - CNN
July 26 (Xinhua) -- According to foreign media reports, on July 18, Nantes, France's religious and historical architectural treasures, the famous Cathedral of St. Peter and St. Paul, was severely damaged in a fire, the large organ was completely destroyed.
On July 26, Nantes prosecutors announced that a parish volunteer responsible for guarding the cathedral had been charged with "arson".
He has admitted that he set the fire in the church.
Local prosecutor Senas said the 39-year-old parish volunteer from Rwanda admitted to lighting three fires in the cathedral during the night, according to reports.
The man's lawyer said the arsonist now regrets having done such a thing.
The man entered France several years ago through the asylum route and was given asylum in the parish where the fire took place, where he was taken in at the church.
The prosecution noted that recently, he tried to renew his visa and is in dialogue and communication with the police department about it.
But the church says it still can't believe that this usually very kind, smiling, but not very talkative believer would destroy the church he loves so much.
On the day of the July 18 fire, the volunteer had already been questioned by police for illogical problems in his account, but he was later released.
The picture shows firefighters at the scene of the rescue.
In the evening of the 25th, the man was summoned again because of new evidence obtained by professional engineers from the laboratory of the Paris Central Police.
This time, the man confessed to the act of arson.
According to reports, the suspect could face 10 years in prison and a fine of 150,000 euros if convicted of intentional arson and destruction.
The fire caused serious damage to the Cathedral of St. Pierre and St. Paul, with the organ inside the church completely destroyed and the stained glass windows behind the organ severely damaged, according to reports.
The chief architect of the French historic preservation building, Brunet, believes that a conservative estimate of the Nantes Cathedral restoration work will take at least three years.
