The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic airliners registered in the U.S. The reason is that the air check valves of the airliners are corroded and may cause the engines to stop in the air.
The FAA said it received four reports of engine air stops on 737NG and 737Classic airliners so far, and thus made an emergency inspection request for airliners that have been parked for seven consecutive days or more and those that have flown less than 11 times since being put back into service.
The FAA warned that if the 5th stage check valves on all two engines of the airliner were corroded, they could seize in the open position, resulting in a complete loss of power and an inability to restart the engines.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valves are found to be corroded, airline operators must replace this critical component before the airliner is put back into service.
Boeing responded later in the day that the new crown outbreak had led to lower demand for travel, and that many airliners had been shut down or used less often, making "check valves more susceptible to corrosion.
Boeing said at the same time, has advised air operators to check the directive involves the airliner, if found problems, Boeing will provide maintenance and replacement of check valves and other aspects of help.
The Associated Press reported that the major U.S. air carriers' passenger planes usually fly multiple times a day, but after the outbreak of the new crown outbreak, a large number of passenger planes grounded; with passenger travel demand has been slowly growing recently, some passenger planes back into operation.
The FAA did not release details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later in the day on the 24th.
The carrier said in a statement that one of its airliners made an emergency landing at Austin Airport on July 15 after one of its engines suddenly stalled on a flight from Seattle, Wash. to Austin, Texas.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the engine on that plane and had followed FAA instructions to check the engines on six aircraft.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that there were no engine flameouts associated with air check valves on their airliners.
American Airlines' four aircraft will be inspected, and United Airlines' 28 aircraft will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect 20 of its planes, but did not say whether there had been engine stalls.
Several media outlets reported that the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive is another blow to Boeing.
A Boeing 737 MAX airliner each from Indonesia's Lion Air and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019, killing a combined 346 people.
