U.S. launches countervailing investigation on China for the first time on the basis of "undervaluation of RMB exchange rate
The U.S. Department of Commerce recently announced its decision to initiate an anti-dumping and countervailing investigation into ties (cable ties) originating in China and to launch an investigation into the "undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate" program.
China's Ministry of Commerce pointed out that this is the first time that the U.S. has opened an investigation into the so-called "RMB exchange rate undervaluation" item in a countervailing case, which China firmly opposes.
China's Ministry of Commerce issued a press release on the 23rd evening, saying that China implements a managed floating exchange rate system based on market supply and demand, adjusted with reference to a basket of currencies, and that the market plays a decisive role in the formation of the exchange rate.
The press release emphasized that, in general, the RMB exchange rate is at a reasonable equilibrium level and is not undervalued.
Since 2005, the RMB has appreciated by more than 17% against the US dollar.
According to data published by the Bank for International Settlements, between early 2005 and May 2020, the nominal effective exchange rate of the RMB appreciated by 38% and the real effective exchange rate by 49%, making it the strongest currency among the G20 economies and one of the most appreciated currencies globally.
The Commerce Department noted that the exchange rate issue is beyond the authority of members to conduct countervailing investigations under World Trade Organization rules.
The U.S. regulation change in February this year to conduct countervailing investigations on other countries' exchange rates has been suspected of violating WTO rules and is opposed by many parties.
Even according to the U.S. regulations, the applicant's complaint contains a large number of errors and does not have the necessary elements of countervailing such as financial support, benefit award and exclusivity, the press release said.
China urged the U.S. side to abide by existing international rules and stop conducting countervailing investigations into the so-called "undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate".
Influenced by the further rise in tensions between the U.S. and China, the offshore and onshore RMB depreciated significantly against the U.S. dollar during the 22nd session, both falling below the RMB7.0 per dollar mark.
Whether the U.S. Department of Commerce's move is intended to force up the yuan deserves attention.
The spot exchange rate of the yuan against the U.S. dollar rose above the 7.0 mark on the 23rd, closing at 6.9961.
The median exchange rate of the yuan against the dollar, which is officially regulated, was lowered by 17 basic points to 6.9938 on the 24th.
