U.S. Congressman and civil rights fighter John Lewis was memorialized as a "fighter for the weakest" at a memorial service held in his honor on Saturday (July 25).
Lewis' public memorial service has been held in Alabama since Saturday.
There were two memorial services on the first day.
At a public memorial service Saturday at Troy University in Alabama, Lewis' five siblings and a nephew and grandson spoke of him as a loving, fearless man who put his family first.
"He devoted his life to helping others," said Henry "Grant" Lewis, Lewis' youngest brother, at the service.
Samuel Lewis said his mother had warned John to "stay out of trouble and stay out of trouble."
He added that John did not heed his mother's warning, saying, "We all knew John would always get into trouble, always in trouble, but it was for sticking to the right thing, which was a good trouble."
Lewis' siblings reminded those at the memorial service that John's most famous argument was to make "good trouble," that is, to not shy away from starting trouble as long as it was for the sake of justice.
John applied to Troy University in Troy, Alabama, where he was born, but the then all-white school rejected his application for admission.
John Lewis, who as a boy preached the gospel to chickens on his family's farm, went on to earn a degree in religion and philosophy from Fisk University.
Years later, Troy University awarded Lewis an honorary doctorate.
Sen. Doug Jones (R-Ala.) said the current protesters "are protesting peacefully and non-violently," as Lewis did during the civil rights movement.
Jones said, "Even if President Trump were to turn the tide and call all the protesters thugs, he would be wrong.
The protesting masses are patriots who want America to move toward a more equal nation."
A six-day series of events to honor Lewis will culminate this week with a funeral in Georgia.
On Saturday Lewis' casket rested at a public memorial at Troy University, where people came to pay their respects to the pioneer of the civil rights movement.
Later Saturday, a private ceremony honored him at a chapel in Selma, Alabama, followed by a public memorial.
On Sunday, Lewis' body will pass over the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma.
It was in front of the bridge that he and demonstrators demanding black voting rights were beaten by Alabama State Police in 1965 and tear gas was used on the demonstrators.
Lewis was nearly killed.
The day came to be known as "Bloody Sunday.
Lewis' body will be transported to Montgomery, the capital of Alabama.
Mayor Steven Reed encouraged people to line the sidewalks and walk with Lewis on this final journey.
