Brazilian study shows hydroxychloroquine ineffective in treating mild to moderate neocrown pneumonia - CNN
A Brazilian study recently showed that hydroxychloroquine was ineffective in treating patients with mild to moderate neoclonal pneumonia.
The study was published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
The Brazilian researchers divided 667 patients from 55 hospitals across the country into three groups and conducted a clinical trial to compare the effects of hydroxychloroquine alone or in combination with the other antibiotic azithromycin, and to analyze whether it helped improve the condition of patients with mild and moderate neocoronary pneumonia.
The results showed that hydroxychloroquine not only had no therapeutic effect, but could have damaging side effects on the organs.
The study was carried out by leading Brazilian hospitals such as Hospital Israelita Albert Einstein, Hospital of Cardiology (HCor), Hospital Sírio-Libanês, in collaboration with the Brazilian Clinical Research Institute (BCRI) and the Brazilian Intensive Care Research Network ( BRICNet).
On the 25th local time, Brazilian President Bossonaro announced through social media platforms that the 4th nucleic acid test result was negative.
During the infection, Bossonaro has been taking hydroxychloroquine and actively promoted it several times.
