U.S. and China trade talks representatives rumored to meet in August
Hong Kong's South China Morning Post reported on 25 August, citing an anonymous source familiar with the matter, that the head of China's trade negotiation team, Vice Premier Liu He, and the co-leader of the U.S. team, Trade Representative Lai Hoi-chul, are expected to hold formal talks in August to assess the two sides' implementation of the first phase of the U.S.-China trade agreement.
The report said that although China has significantly increased its purchases of U.S. agricultural products in the past few months, the Chinese purchases are still some distance away from the quantities promised in the trade agreement because of the new coronavirus outbreak and other factors.
Analysts say recent U.S.-China closures of each other's consulates, along with other disputes, could derail any progress on trade between the two sides.
The first phase of the U.S.-China trade deal, which took effect a month after it was signed on Jan. 15, stipulates that a trade framework group of top officials from both sides should meet every six months.
The source said the meeting would be "an important turning point" that would allow the two sides to assess progress on the agreement.
But the source also said that if U.S.-China tensions lead to a lack of willingness to talk at this time, the two sides may agree that the May 8 conference call between Lai Haider and Liu He has met the semi-annual meeting clause of the trade agreement.
Since this year, Sino-US relations have deteriorated rapidly, with disputes between the two sides including a series of issues such as the origin of the new crown virus, trade, Hong Kong, Xinjiang, the South China Sea and ideology.
Although U.S. President Donald Trump bragged about his achievements in the first phase of the agreement at the beginning of the year, his attitude has changed recently.
He said at a White House press conference on the 23rd that although China has recently made record-breaking single-day purchases of U.S. corn and bought a lot of soybeans, "this trade deal is not as meaningful to me now as it was when it was reached."
An anonymous Beijing government adviser also believes that a new round of trade talks is unlikely due to poor U.S.-China relations, and that "trade issues have lost weight in U.S.-China relations.
But he revealed that Chinese economic and trade related units still met on the 23rd to discuss a range of issues, including how to increase imports from the U.S. "We've done our best to buy, so any additional purchases would be difficult."
U.S.-China National Trade Council Vice President Peng Jie-ning said it was "more important than ever" to maintain the momentum of the first phase of the agreement, and said China has made progress this year in further opening its financial markets to U.S. companies.
Analysts at Plenum, an independent research firm, said "talk is better than no talk, even though it may only be treated as routine."
