Zhang Haochen, with his deep and concise understanding, played the first theme of the work, which is full of sorrow and entanglement, and under the baton of Yang Yang, the orchestra and the piano created a continuous aural enjoyment in the ebb and flow of competition and compromise.
After experiencing the "Watery Silence" in the second movement and the "Grand Carnival" in the third movement, the audience of more than one hundred burst out in applause at the moving experience of returning to the scene, and the online audience also expressed their heartfelt admiration by means of pop-ups and comments.
Zhang Haochen then returned to the audience with a return encore performance of Chopin's posthumous Nocturne in C minor.
After a brief stage adjustment, Yang Yang conducted the NCPA Orchestra in Rachmaninoff's last work for large orchestra, Symphonic Dances, in which the composer presented a more introspective emotion and incorporated his new inspirations and memories of past compositions and his homeland.
The melancholy and grandeur of this work was revealed in Yang Yang's calm and composed handling of the work, and the orchestra's interpretation of Rachmaninoff's "The Last Spark" was brilliant.
The pre-concert introduction of this concert once again brought unexpected surprises to the audience.
CCTV News anchor Gang Qiang came to the backstage dressing room of the NCPA to reveal the "stronghold" of music masters such as Dzhejev and Lang Lang before they appeared on stage. In the end of the guided tour, Gang Qiang also performed Schumann's "Fantasia" with Zhang Haochen, to the delight of the audience.
In the evening, in the NCPA's Taiko Amphitheater, the military chorus song concert started with the melodious "Not Forgetting the First Heart".
This is the first performance of the National Grand Theatre's "Taihu Week Concert" since the epidemic.
