APEC members' trade ministers' meeting says to accelerate regional economic recovery-Xinhua
KUALA LUMPUR, July 25 (Xinhua) -- The Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) members' trade ministers' video conference held on July 25 pledged to work to reduce the impact of the new crown epidemic on the region's economy and accelerate efforts to achieve a resilient, sustainable and inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was hosted by Malaysia, the host of this year's informal APEC Leaders' Meeting.
A joint statement issued after the meeting said APEC member trade ministers recognized the importance of a free, open, fair, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment to drive economic recovery at this challenging time.
The parties committed to ensure that emergency measures taken in response to the outbreak are targeted, appropriate, transparent and temporary, do not create unnecessary barriers to trade and disrupt global supply chains, and comply with World Trade Organization rules.
In their statement, APEC member trade ministers pledged to strengthen cooperation to facilitate the flow of goods and services necessary to minimize disruptions to the flow of medical supplies, food and agricultural products in response to the outbreak by enhancing supply chain resilience and promoting connectivity.
APEC member trade ministers agreed on the need to discuss ways to reduce non-tariff barriers that restrict trade in essential goods and reaffirmed their commitment to facilitate the necessary cross-border movement of people without compromising the measures taken to stop the spread of the epidemic.
The meeting also issued a declaration on facilitating the flow of essential commodities.
The declaration said that economies will ensure that trade measures they take in response to the outbreak are WTO-compliant and commit to take action in reducing non-tariff barriers to trade, trade facilitation, etc. to facilitate the necessary movement of goods under the outbreak.
Presiding over the meeting, Malaysian Minister of International Trade and Industry Azmin Ali said that despite the impact of the epidemic, Malaysia remains committed to the success of this year's APEC meeting, and work to develop a vision for APEC cooperation beyond 2020 is progressing in an orderly manner.
Malaysia agreed to hold APEC-related meetings in video format, but did not rule out the possibility of arranging a physical meeting at the end of the year when the APEC leaders meet informally.
