France increases military investment in space - Xinhua
French Defense Minister Florence Paley said on the 24th that France will add hundreds of millions of euros to its space defense budget to develop military forces in space to prevent possible "unfriendly moves" by other countries in outer space.
Paley told Le Provençal the same day that the budget for spending on French military space programs will increase to 4.3 billion euros ($5 billion) from 3.6 billion euros ($4.2 billion) previously proposed for the period 2019 to 2025.
According to the French Military Planning Act 2019 to 2025, approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to update existing observation and communication satellites, launch three electromagnetic listening satellites and improve the modernization of space surveillance radars in the future.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced last July that a military command for space and an "air and space force" would be established within the French Air Force.
Paley said she will formally announce the establishment of this space force when she visits a military school in Saron, Provence, later.
The space force, which is part of the Air Force, will have a strength of 500 by 2025, Paley said.
Gone are the days when people thought space served the common good of science," she said. Today space is a site where nations compete for global hegemony."
Paley reiterated Macron's earlier statement that France has no intention of provoking an arms race.
"We are in no way engaged in an arms race. But it is my responsibility to thoroughly recognize the threats we may face."
Paley revisited the 2017 surveillance of a military satellite shared by France and Italy.
She claimed that it was a Russian satellite that was "spied on."
The Russians deny the claim.
Paley said France would "soon" have small patrol satellites capable of detecting and targeting "those who are behind unfriendly moves.
French media believe that the reason why France seeks to establish a space force, because U.S. President Donald Trump asked the U.S. Department of Defense in February last year to draft a bill to set up a space force.
Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act in December last year, approving the establishment of the United States' sixth major military service, the TAF.
Some experts worry that these U.S. initiatives have accelerated the pace of U.S. space militarization and may trigger a new round of space arms race.
