3-year-old child smashed in university playground, compensated and then sued the university is justified?
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source：Legal Daily Author：Wang Sishuo Responsibility Editor：Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed, the child was compensated and then sued the school
□ Our correspondent Zhao Yifan
3-year-old Xiao Wen was playing in a university playground when he was accidentally hit in the head by Chen Mou of the softball team while throwing a ball.
After Chen compensated, Mr. Wen, the father of Xiaowen, as the legal representative of Xiaowen, took the school to court, demanding the school where the playground was located to pay for the damages and apologize, as well as pay medical expenses and moral damage compensation totaling 20,000 yuan.
Recently, the Beijing Haidian District People's Court heard the case and held that the school had set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident and had done its duty to ensure proper safety, and Chen had made compensation, according to which the judgment rejected the plaintiff's claim.
Mr. Wen claimed that he took Xiaowen to play in the school playground during the summer vacation in 2019, when the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid the resulting risks, Xiaowen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents were in the safe area designated by the softball team.
However, Chen, a member of the softball team, took off his hand while throwing the ball, causing it to fly over the safety net and hit Xiao Wen in the back of his head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believed that the school's field facilities did not meet the relevant safety regulations and failed to effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The school's negligence led to the above incident, resulting in great physical and mental suffering for Xiaowen, as well as greater pain for his family, for which the school should be held legally responsible.
In this regard, the school argued that the school has set up a protective net in the playground, and posted the management regulations, training notices, informed the playground to maintain a safe distance from the training ground and reminded to pay attention to their own safety, the plaintiff also can not prove that the school "did not do their duty to ensure safety", so do not agree to compensation.
The court heard that the site of the incident is the University of the public free site, the school although the management of the playground there is a duty of safety, but this duty of safety only need to meet the general duty of care can be.
The school set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, has done its proper safety obligations, and Chen also in accordance with the previously reached compensation agreement to the small Wen compensation for medical expenses, transportation costs and other losses of more than two thousand dollars, the two sides agreed to a one-time settlement of the dispute.
Afterwards, Xiaowen's parents again claimed that the school compensation, there is no basis in law, the court ruled to dismiss the plaintiff's entire claim.
After the verdict, both sides did not appeal, the verdict is now in effect.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, the school, as the manager of the public place, has the duty of safety and security; in the case of damage caused by the actions of a third party, the third party bears the tort liability, while the public place manager who failed to do his duty of safety and security should bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
The judge said, as the manager of the public place, the most likely to understand the actual situation of the whole place, foresee the possible danger and damage, and thus the most likely to take the necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or mitigate the degree of damage, and the lowest cost to avoid and mitigate the occurrence of damage, so the law provides that the corresponding protection obligations by its social activities.
In this case, the school's safety obligations should be adapted to the social activities it engages in, specifically, the basic safety measures and the obligation to inform the public of hidden dangers, for the unspecified group of people entering the playground, which is open to the public free of charge.
In judicial practice, it is not advisable to impose excessive safety obligations on the managers of public places.
If the school has taken the steps to set up a protective net and has fulfilled its duty to inform, the school can be found not at fault and should not be held liable.
In addition, for third party torts, even if the manager of a public place such as a school fails to fulfill its safety obligations, its liability is supplemented by damages, and according to the latest Civil Code, the manager can recover from the third party after assuming supplementary liability.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victim should not expand the scope of the claim after receiving compensation from the direct infringer.
