Xinjing News (Reporter Liu Zhen) July 26, the Beijing Philharmonic Choir published an obituary, the founder of the Beijing Philharmonic Choir, the famous Chinese conductor, music educator, tenured academic member of the Central Conservatory of Music, professor of the Department of Conducting Yang Hongnian, died at 13:55 on July 26, 2020 in Beijing at the age of 86 due to medical treatment.
Photo from the official website of Beijing Philharmonic Choir.
Yang Hongnian was born in 1934 in Nanjing, Jiangsu Province, and loved music since he was a child.
In 1951, he became the conductor of the chorus of Nanjing People's Broadcasting Station. In the fall of 1951, he entered the music department of East China Normal University in Shanghai, where he studied conducting under Professor Yang Jaren and German conductor Hitzmann, and studied the form and polyphony with former Soviet expert Arzamanov.
In 1958, he taught at the Music Department of Beijing Art Teachers' College, and in 1973, he moved to the Central Conservatory of Music to teach at the Composition and Conducting Departments.
Yang Hongnian founded the Beijing Philharmonic Choir in 1983.
For more than thirty years, he has led this choir to sing all over the world, and has won dozens of awards in important competitions at home and abroad, adhering to the tenet of "love and devotion".
He has conducted more than 30 groups such as the Chorus of the Central Orchestra, the Central National Song and Dance Company, the Oriental Song and Dance Company, and the Shanghai Chorus, as well as many symphonic concerts and choral concerts.
His books include "Band Training", "Choral Training", "Two Part Song Writing", "Children's Songbook" (upper and lower volumes), and essays "On the Problem of Choral Pitch" and "On the Layout of Acoustic Layers in Orchestral Music", as well as translations of "Choral Orchestration" and "Debussy's Harmonic Language".
