2020-07-26 04:56:44 Source：Bright Daily Author：Wang Sishuo Responsibility Editor：Wang Sishuo
Israel strengthens prevention and control against recurring outbreaks
At the beginning of the outbreak of the new crown pneumonia, Israel's preventive and control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of the ban on preventive and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of Newcastle pneumonia in Israel has recently increased significantly, and the Israeli government has taken several emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of Newcastle pneumonia was confirmed in Israel, and the government quickly took measures to close all ports of entry and exit, suspend non-essential industries, convert schools to online classes, restrict public transportation and non-essential social activities, seal off cities with severe outbreaks, and combine military and police efforts to maintain prevention and control initiatives.
This series of measures quickly yielded positive results, and by mid-May, the number of confirmed new cases of pneumonia in Israel dropped to single digits on a single day.
As the epidemic was brought under control and Israeli preventive and control measures were fully unblocked, the number of confirmed new cases of NCCP gradually rebounded since June.
Especially after July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
Recently, there were 8 days with more than 1,500 new cases per day in Israel, and as of press time on July 25, the number of new cases reached 916 on that day.
As of July 25, there were 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
In the face of the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has taken several emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gyms, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other public entertainment venues, while introducing a policy of limiting public transportation to a maximum of 20 passengers per bus.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a new series of restrictions, including the implementation of the "city closure" on weekends, which is implemented between 17:00 on Fridays and 5:00 on Sundays.
During this period, people can go out, but stores, shopping centers, barber stores, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while supermarkets, pharmacies and other basic services will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people will be banned on all days and hours, gyms, studios and other places will be closed, and restaurants and cafes will be banned from dine-in and only take-out service will be allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli public did not pay enough attention to the severity of the epidemic and failed to join forces with the government in the fight against it.
After the recurrence of the epidemic in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest against the government's preventive and control measures that affected their economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people demonstrated in Tel Aviv, arguing that anti-epidemic policies were affecting the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's residence in Jerusalem to protest against the ban on restaurants and cafes without compensation.
In addition, many people did not comply with the rules of wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters when outdoors. To avoid being fined by police for not wearing masks, many people simply wore them on their chins or hung them on their wrists.
According to a recent visit to the kindergarten, teachers and students did not wear masks as required by the government and did not keep a safe social distance of two meters from each other, which laid the groundwork for a large number of teachers and students to be infected with the virus.
Professor Elie Waxman, a member of the Israeli National Security Council's expert advisory group to combat the epidemic, believes that Israel is heading toward a "dangerous situation," pointing out that the current measures taken by Israel to prevent and control the epidemic are not enough, and that all leisure and recreational activities and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks a general plan to fight the epidemic and that the Knesset and all government departments should quickly put aside their own interests and agree on the fight against the epidemic and formulate clear steps that include relevant restrictions in different sectors.
