Lancet article praises China's efforts to fight epidemic, encourages countries to learn from experience - CNN
China, a country with a population of 1.4 billion and a scale similar to that of Europe or the United States, has largely contained the domestic epidemic at this stage by effectively controlling the new crown epidemic without any further widespread spread, said an article in The Lancet 25.
The article says that China has invested heavily in domestic research and public health construction over the last decade or so, which has made it much more prepared for the new crown than it was for severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) that year.
When the SARS outbreak occurred in 2002, the authors say, China was initially ill-prepared, especially because the pathogen could not be identified.
When the new coronavirus was discovered in December 2019, Chinese scientists were quickly able to identify the virus species and shared the genome sequencing data internationally on Jan. 11, 2020.
By the end of January, doctors from mainland China and Hong Kong elucidated the clinical features of the virus, warning the world of the threat of the new coronavirus through a research paper published in The Lancet.
China has also been at the forefront of vaccine research, and such research has been conducted very quickly and rigorously through close collaboration within the country in the face of a declared national emergency, with results of progress in early trials of a new coronavirus vaccine developed in China published in The Lancet in May and July, respectively.
The Chinese experience demonstrates the importance of investing in the national health and research system to effectively improve laboratory capacity.
This is the basis for a rapid and effective national response to health emergencies and global health security.
It is well worthwhile for other countries, especially low- and middle-income countries, to learn from and emulate this.
In addition, China's experience proves that a strong research base must be followed by strong top-level decisiveness to make the right decisions based on scientific evidence, which has led to effective control of the new crown outbreak.
The article emphasizes that the government and its leaders must respect science, understand its value, and act on it in the way that is best for society.
In the early stages of the outbreak, China's National Health Construction Commission sent three teams of infectious disease experts to Wuhan to investigate the risk and spread of the New Guinea virus, and their recommendations informed the decision to "seal off" the city on January 23; when experts raised the need and urgency of building the Fangzhai Hospital, the government made a quick decision and implemented it quickly; and At the same time, widespread community and public participation enabled the outbreak to be contained quickly and effectively.
The article concludes by emphasizing that countries need to strengthen global cooperation and joint response to global health emergencies.
