Hong Kong, July 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong SAR Government Secretary for Commerce and Economic Development Edward Yau said on July 25 that all APEC member economies should act in concert to fight the epidemic and promote economic recovery, and should avoid building unnecessary trade barriers in accordance with the rights and obligations set by the World Trade Organization.
Qiu Teng Hua made the remarks while attending a video conference of trade ministers on the fight against the new pneumonia epidemic at APEC 25.
At the meeting, the ministers exchanged views on APEC's response to the impact of the new pneumonia epidemic and on substantive programs that could be adopted to promote economic recovery in the region.
Qiu Teng Hua said the public health and economic crisis triggered by the outbreak has had unprecedented and far-reaching social and economic impacts.
"We are in a double battle, we must overcome the epidemic before we can recover the economy.
We need to be clear in our goal that the virus is our common enemy and that cooperation will lead to victory, and the opposite will only lead to defeat."
Chiu Teng Hwa said the series of trade restrictions triggered by the new pneumonia outbreak will not help control the epidemic.
Trade is the key solution to the current problem and should not be seen as the problem.
He condemned all discriminatory and divisive policy measures and urged all economies to keep their borders open and supply chains running smoothly at this critical time, and to avoid building trade barriers or adopting irrational trade policies.
